1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:08,000
This ivy-covered tree
is slowly reaching
the end of its long life.

2
00:00:08,000 --> 00:00:16,000
If we move the ivy,
we can find a small sign.

3
00:00:16,000 --> 00:00:24,000
It says this is a pedunculate oak
called "The End and The Beginning".

4
00:00:24,000 --> 00:00:32,000
The name comes from
a colorful art project

5
00:00:32,000 --> 00:00:40,000
made in 2012
by artist Łukasz Berg.

6
00:00:40,000 --> 00:00:48,000
Even then, the tree no longer
looked like a proud
natural monument.

7
00:00:48,000 --> 00:00:56,000
Its meaning also changed.
As art, it was meant
to show friendship,

8
00:00:56,000 --> 00:01:04,000
peace, and including
everyone together.

9
00:01:04,000 --> 00:01:12,000
But how did this oak
end up in the village center?

10
00:01:12,000 --> 00:01:20,000
It was planted in the dark 1930s,
when this land was ruled
by Nazi Germany.

11
00:01:20,000 --> 00:01:28,000
It honored victims
of World War I,
but also Nazi ideas.

12
00:01:28,000 --> 00:01:36,000
Planting oaks was meant
to be a symbol of power
and long life.

13
00:01:36,000 --> 00:01:46,000
They believed their empire
would last a thousand years,
like strong old oaks.

14
00:01:46,000 --> 00:01:54,000
But it ended quickly.
The empire fell before
the oak even grew up.

15
00:01:54,000 --> 00:01:54,000
This shows that big ideas
can fade faster
than a simple tree.